const faqs = [{"question": "Can peptides cure arthritis?", "answer": "No. Peptide therapy cannot cure arthritis, particularly osteoarthritis where structural cartilage damage has already occurred. However, peptides may help manage symptoms, reduce inflammation, slow progression, and improve quality of life as part of a complete treatment plan under physician supervision."}, {"question": "Are peptides safe for older adults with arthritis?", "answer": "Peptide therapy can be appropriate for older adults when supervised by a physician who accounts for the patient's complete medical history, current medications, and overall health status. Age alone is not a contraindication, and older adults may benefit significantly from the anti-inflammatory and tissue-supporting properties of certain peptides."}, {"question": "How long before peptides help with joint pain?", "answer": "Many patients report improvement in joint pain and stiffness within 2–4 weeks of starting peptide therapy. More substantial benefits, including improved mobility and reduced need for pain medications, typically develop over 6–12 weeks. Individual response varies based on the severity and type of arthritis."}, {"question": "Can I use peptides alongside my current arthritis medications?", "answer": "In many cases, peptide therapy can complement existing arthritis treatments. However, potential interactions must be evaluated by your physician. Some patients are able to reduce their reliance on NSAIDs or corticosteroids after initiating peptide therapy, but any medication changes should be made under medical supervision."}, {"question": "Is peptide therapy covered by Medicare or insurance for arthritis?", "answer": "Peptide therapy for arthritis is generally not covered by Medicare or commercial insurance, as it is considered an off-label use. Strong Health provides transparent pricing and can discuss costs during your initial consultation."}, {"question": "What types of arthritis respond best to peptide therapy?", "answer": "Osteoarthritis and inflammatory arthritis (including mild-to-moderate rheumatoid arthritis) may respond to peptide therapy. Patients with mechanical joint pain from cartilage degeneration and those with chronic low-grade joint inflammation tend to report the most benefit. Severe inflammatory autoimmune arthritis typically requires immunosuppressive medications as the primary treatment."}, {"question": "Can peptides help after joint replacement surgery?", "answer": "BPC-157 and TB-500 may support recovery after joint replacement surgery by promoting tissue healing, reducing inflammation, and supporting rehabilitation. However, peptide therapy for post-surgical recovery should be coordinated between your surgeon and prescribing physician."}];

